# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: graph-minors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In graph theory, an undirected graph H is called a **minor** of the undirected graph G if H can be formed from G by deleting edges and vertices and by contracting edges.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The theory of graph minors began with Wagner's theorem that a graph is planar if and only if its minors include neither the complete graph *K*5 nor the complete bipartite graph *K*3,3.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The Robertson–Seymour theorem implies that an analogous forbidden minor characterization exists for every property of graphs that is preserved by deletions and edge contractions.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] For every fixed graph H, it is possible to test whether H is a minor of an input graph G in polynomial time; together with the forbidden minor characterization this implies that every graph property preserved by deletions and contractions may be recognized in polynomial time.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Important variants of graph minors include the topological minors and immersion minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] An edge contraction is an operation that removes an edge from a graph while simultaneously merging the two vertices it used to connect.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] An undirected graph H is a minor of another undirected graph G if a graph isomorphic to H can be obtained from G by contracting some edges, deleting some edges, and deleting some isolated vertices.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The order in which a sequence of such contractions and deletions is performed on G does not affect the resulting graph H.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Graph minors are often studied in the more general context of matroid minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In this context, it is common to assume that all graphs are connected, with self-loops and multiple edges allowed (that is, they are multigraphs rather than simple graphs); the contraction of a loop and the deletion of a cut-edge are forbidden operations.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] This point of view has the advantage that edge deletions leave the rank of a graph unchanged, and edge contractions always reduce the rank by one.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In other contexts (such as with the study of pseudoforests) it makes more sense to allow the deletion of a cut-edge, and to allow disconnected graphs, but to forbid multigraphs.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In this variation of graph minor theory, a graph is always simplified after any edge contraction to eliminate its self-loops and multiple edges.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A function f is referred to as "minor-monotone" if, whenever H is a minor of G, one has *f*(*H*) ≤ *f*(*G*).
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A deep result by Neil Robertson and Paul Seymour states that this partial order is actually a well-quasi-ordering: if an infinite list (*G*1, *G*2, …) of finite graphs is given, then there always exist two indices *i* < *j* such that Gi is a minor of Gj.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Another equivalent way of stating this is that any set of graphs can have only a finite number of minimal elements under the minor ordering.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] This result proved a conjecture formerly known as Wagner's conjecture, after Klaus Wagner; Wagner had conjectured it long earlier, but only published it in 1970.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In the course of their proof, Seymour and Robertson also prove the graph structure theorem in which they determine, for any fixed graph H, the rough structure of any graph that does not have H as a minor.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The statement of the theorem is itself long and involved, but in short it establishes that such a graph must have the structure of a clique-sum of smaller graphs that are modified in small ways from graphs embedded on surfaces of bounded genus.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Thus, their theory establishes fundamental connections between graph minors and topological embeddings of graphs.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] For any graph H, the simple H-minor-free graphs must be sparse, which means that the number of edges is less than some constant multiple of the number of vertices.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] More specifically, if H has h vertices, then a simple n-vertex simple H-minor-free graph can have at most $\scriptstyle O(nh{\sqrt {\log h}})$ edges, and some Kh-minor-free graphs have at least this many edges.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Thus, if H has h vertices, then H-minor-free graphs have average degree $\scriptstyle O(h{\sqrt {\log h}})$ and furthermore degeneracy $\scriptstyle O(h{\sqrt {\log h}})$ .
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Even stronger, for any fixed H, H-minor-free graphs have treewidth $\scriptstyle O({\sqrt {n}})$ .
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The Hadwiger conjecture in graph theory proposes that if a graph G does not contain a minor isomorphic to the complete graph on k vertices, then G has a proper coloring with *k* – 1 colors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The case *k* = 5 is a restatement of the four color theorem.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The Hadwiger conjecture has been proven for *k* ≤ 6, but is unknown in the general case.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Bollobás, Catlin & Erdős (1980) call it "one of the deepest unsolved problems in graph theory." Another result relating the four-color theorem to graph minors is the snark theorem announced by Robertson, Sanders, Seymour, and Thomas, a strengthening of the four-color theorem conjectured by W.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Tutte and stating that any bridgeless 3-regular graph that requires four colors in an edge coloring must have the Petersen graph as a minor.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Many families of graphs have the property that every minor of a graph in *F* is also in *F*; such a class is said to be *minor-closed*.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] For instance, in any planar graph, or any embedding of a graph on a fixed topological surface, neither the removal of edges nor the contraction of edges can increase the genus of the embedding; therefore, planar graphs and the graphs embeddable on any fixed surface form minor-closed families.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] If *F* is a minor-closed family, then (because of the well-quasi-ordering property of minors) among the graphs that do not belong to *F* there is a finite set *X* of minor-minimal graphs.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] These graphs are forbidden minors for *F*: a graph belongs to *F* if and only if it does not contain as a minor any graph in *X*.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] That is, every minor-closed family *F* can be characterized as the family of *X*-minor-free graphs for some finite set *X* of forbidden minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The best-known example of a characterization of this type is Wagner's theorem characterizing the planar graphs as the graphs having neither K5 nor K3,3 as minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In some cases, the properties of the graphs in a minor-closed family may be closely connected to the properties of their excluded minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] If *H* can be drawn in the plane with only a single crossing (that is, it has crossing number one) then the *H*-minor-free graphs have a simplified structure theorem in which they are formed as clique-sums of planar graphs and graphs of bounded treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] For instance, both *K*5 and *K*3,3 have crossing number one, and as Wagner showed the *K*5-free graphs are exactly the 3-clique-sums of planar graphs and the eight-vertex Wagner graph, while the *K*3,3-free graphs are exactly the 2-clique-sums of planar graphs and *K*5.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A graph *H* is called a **topological minor** of a graph *G* if a subdivision of *H* is isomorphic to a subgraph of *G*.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Every topological minor is also a minor.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The converse however is not true in general (for instance the complete graph *K*5 in the Petersen graph is a minor but not a topological one), but holds for graph with maximum degree not greater than three.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The topological minor relation is not a well-quasi-ordering on the set of finite graphs and hence the result of Robertson and Seymour does not apply to topological minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] However it is straightforward to construct finite forbidden topological minor characterizations from finite forbidden minor characterizations by replacing every branch set with *k* outgoing edges by every tree on *k* leaves that has down degree at least two.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A graph *H* is called an **induced minor** of a graph *G* if it can be obtained from an induced subgraph of *G* by contracting edges.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Otherwise, *G* is said to be *H*-induced minor-free.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Induced minors have been used to study string graphs, the intersection graphs of plane curves, because every induced minor of a string graph is another string graph.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The string graphs provide an example of a family of graphs with infinitely many obstacles in the induced minor order, where an obstacle is a graph that is not in the family but for which all proper induced minors are in the family.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A graph operation called *lifting* is central in a concept called *immersions*.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The *lifting* is an operation on adjacent edges.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Given three vertices *v*, *u*, and *w*, where *(v,u)* and *(u,w)* are edges in the graph, the lifting of *vuw*, or equivalent of *(v,u), (u,w)* is the operation that deletes the two edges *(v,u)* and *(u,w)* and adds the edge *(v,w)*.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In the case where *(v,w)* already was present, *v* and *w* will now be connected by more than one edge, and hence this operation is intrinsically a multi-graph operation.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In the case where a graph *H* can be obtained from a graph *G* by a sequence of lifting operations (on *G*) and then finding an isomorphic subgraph, we say that *H* is an immersion minor of *G*.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] There is yet another way of defining immersion minors, which is equivalent to the lifting operation.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] We say that *H* is an immersion minor of *G* if there exists an injective mapping from vertices in *H* to vertices in *G* where the images of adjacent elements of *H* are connected in *G* by edge-disjoint paths.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The immersion minor relation is a well-quasi-ordering on the set of finite graphs and hence the result of Robertson and Seymour applies to immersion minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] This furthermore means that every immersion minor-closed family is characterized by a finite family of forbidden immersion minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In graph drawing, immersion minors arise as the planarizations of non-planar graphs: from a drawing of a graph in the plane, with crossings, one can form an immersion minor by replacing each crossing point by a new vertex, and in the process also subdividing each crossed edge into a path.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] This allows drawing methods for planar graphs to be extended to non-planar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A shallow minor of a graph *G* is a minor in which the edges of *G* that were contracted to form the minor form a collection of disjoint subgraphs with low diameter.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Shallow minors interpolate between the theories of graph minors and subgraphs, in that shallow minors with high depth coincide with the usual type of graph minor, while the shallow minors with depth zero are exactly the subgraphs.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] They also allow the theory of graph minors to be extended to classes of graphs such as the 1-planar graphs that are not closed under taking minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] An odd minor restricts this definition by adding parity conditions to these subtrees.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Unlike for the usual kind of graph minors, graphs with forbidden odd minors are not necessarily sparse.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The Hadwiger conjecture, that *k*-chromatic graphs necessarily contain *k*-vertex complete graphs as minors, has also been studied from the point of view of odd minors.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A different parity-based extension of the notion of graph minors is the concept of a bipartite minor, which produces a bipartite graph whenever the starting graph is bipartite.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A graph *H* is a bipartite minor of another graph *G* whenever *H* can be obtained from *G* by deleting vertices, deleting edges, and collapsing pairs of vertices that are at distance two from each other along a peripheral cycle of the graph.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] A form of Wagner's theorem applies for bipartite minors: A bipartite graph *G* is a planar graph if and only if it does not have the utility graph *K*3,3 as a bipartite minor.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] The problem of deciding whether a graph *G* contains *H* as a minor is NP-complete in general; for instance, if *H* is a cycle graph with the same number of vertices as *G*, then *H* is a minor of *G* if and only if *G* contains a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] However, when *G* is part of the input but *H* is fixed, it can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Thus, by applying the polynomial time algorithm for testing whether a given graph contains any of the forbidden minors, it is theoretically possible to recognize the members of any minor-closed family in polynomial time.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] This result is not used in practice since the hidden constant is so huge (needing three layers of Knuth's up-arrow notation to express) as to rule out any application, making it a galactic algorithm.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] Furthermore, in order to apply this result constructively, it is necessary to know what the forbidden minors of the graph family are.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In some cases, the forbidden minors are known, or can be computed.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In the case where *H* is a fixed planar graph, then we can test in linear time in an input graph *G* whether *H* is a minor of *G*.
[src:graph-minors/graph-minor] In cases where *H* is not fixed, faster algorithms are known in the case where *G* is planar.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In graph theory, a **planar graph** is a graph that can be embedded in the plane, i.e., it can be drawn on the plane in such a way that its edges intersect only at their endpoints.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In other words, it can be drawn in such a way that no edges cross each other.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Such a drawing is called a **plane graph**, or a **planar embedding** of the graph.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A plane graph can be defined as a planar graph with a mapping from every node to a point on a plane, and from every edge to a plane curve on that plane, such that the extreme points of each curve are the points mapped from its end nodes, and all curves are disjoint except on their extreme points.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Every graph that can be drawn on a plane can be drawn on the sphere as well, and vice versa, by means of stereographic projection.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Plane graphs can be encoded with combinatorial maps or rotation systems.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] An equivalence class of topologically equivalent drawings on the sphere, usually with additional assumptions such as connectedness, is called a **planar map**.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Although a plane graph has an **external** or **unbounded** face, none of the faces of a planar map has a particular status.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Planar graphs generalize to graphs drawable on a surface of a given genus.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In this terminology, planar graphs have genus 0, since the plane (and the sphere) are surfaces of genus 0.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] See "graph embedding" for other related topics.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A subdivision of a graph results from inserting vertices into edges (for example, changing an edge • —— • to • — • — • ) zero or more times.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A minor of a graph results from taking a subgraph and repeatedly contracting an edge into a vertex, with each neighbor of the original end-vertices becoming a neighbor of the new vertex.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Klaus Wagner asked more generally whether any minor-closed class of graphs is determined by a finite set of "forbidden minors".
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] This is now the Robertson–Seymour theorem, proved in a long series of papers.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In the language of this theorem, *K*5 and *K*3,3 are the forbidden minors for the class of finite planar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In practice, it is difficult to use Kuratowski's criterion to quickly decide whether a given graph is planar.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] However, there exist fast algorithms for this problem: for a graph with n vertices, it is possible to determine in time *O*(*n*) (linear time) whether the graph may be planar or not (see planarity testing).
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In this sense, planar graphs are sparse graphs, in that they have only *O*(*v*) edges, asymptotically smaller than the maximum *O*(*v*2).
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The graph *K*3,3, for example, has 6 vertices, 9 edges, and no cycles of length 3.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Therefore, by Theorem 2, it cannot be planar.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] These theorems provide necessary conditions for planarity that are not sufficient conditions, and therefore can only be used to prove a graph is not planar, not that it is planar.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] If both theorem 1 and 2 fail, other methods may be used.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] As an illustration, in the butterfly graph given above, *v* = 5, *e* = 6 and *f* = 3.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In general, if the property holds for all planar graphs of f faces, any change to the graph that creates an additional face while keeping the graph planar would keep *v* − *e* + *f* an invariant.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Since the property holds for all graphs with *f* = 2, by mathematical induction it holds for all cases.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Euler's formula can also be proved as follows: if the graph isn't a tree, then remove an edge which completes a cycle.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] This lowers both e and f by one, leaving *v* − *e* + *f* constant.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Repeat until the remaining graph is a tree; trees have *v* = *e* + 1 and *f* = 1, yielding *v* − *e* + *f* = 2, i. e., the Euler characteristic is 2.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Euler's formula is also valid for convex polyhedra.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] This is no coincidence: every convex polyhedron can be turned into a connected, simple, planar graph by using the Schlegel diagram of the polyhedron, a perspective projection of the polyhedron onto a plane with the center of perspective chosen near the center of one of the polyhedron's faces.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Not every planar graph corresponds to a convex polyhedron in this way: the trees do not, for example.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Steinitz's theorem says that the polyhedral graphs formed from convex polyhedra are precisely the finite 3-connected simple planar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] More generally, Euler's formula applies to any polyhedron whose faces are simple polygons that form a surface topologically equivalent to a sphere, regardless of its convexity.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Connected planar graphs with more than one edge obey the inequality 2*e* ≥ 3*f*, because each face has at least three face-edge incidences and each edge contributes exactly two incidences.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] It follows via algebraic transformations of this inequality with Euler's formula *v* − *e* + *f* = 2 that for finite planar graphs the average degree is strictly less than 6.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Graphs with higher average degree cannot be planar.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] We say that two circles drawn in a plane *kiss* (or *osculate*) whenever they intersect in exactly one point.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A "coin graph" is a graph formed by a set of circles, no two of which have overlapping interiors, by making a vertex for each circle and an edge for each pair of circles that kiss.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The circle packing theorem, first proved by Paul Koebe in 1936, states that a graph is planar if and only if it is a coin graph.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] This result provides an easy proof of Fáry's theorem, that every simple planar graph can be embedded in the plane in such a way that its edges are straight line segments that do not cross each other.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] If one places each vertex of the graph at the center of the corresponding circle in a coin graph representation, then the line segments between centers of kissing circles do not cross any of the other edges.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The density obeys 0 ≤ *D* ≤ 1, with *D* = 0 for a completely sparse planar graph (a tree), and *D* = 1 for a completely dense (maximal) planar graph.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Furthermore, this edge is drawn so that it crosses e exactly once and that no other edge of G or G* is intersected.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Then G* is again the embedding of a (not necessarily simple) planar graph; it has as many edges as G, as many vertices as G has faces and as many faces as G has vertices.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The term "dual" is justified by the fact that *G*** = *G*; here the equality is the equivalence of embeddings on the sphere.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] If G is the planar graph corresponding to a convex polyhedron, then G* is the planar graph corresponding to the dual polyhedron.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Duals are useful because many properties of the dual graph are related in simple ways to properties of the original graph, enabling results to be proven about graphs by examining their dual graphs.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] While the dual constructed for a particular embedding is unique (up to isomorphism), graphs may have different (i.e. non-isomorphic) duals, obtained from different (i.e. non-homeomorphic) embeddings.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A simple graph is called **maximal planar** if it is planar but adding any edge (on the given vertex set) would destroy that property.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] All faces (including the outer one) are then bounded by three edges, explaining the alternative term **plane triangulation** (which technically means a plane drawing of the graph).
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The alternative names "triangular graph" or "triangulated graph" have also been used, but are ambiguous, as they commonly refer to the line graph of a complete graph and to the chordal graphs respectively.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Every maximal planar graph on more than 3 vertices is at least 3-connected.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] If a maximal planar graph has v vertices with *v* > 2, then it has precisely 3*v* − 6 edges and 2*v* − 4 faces.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Apollonian networks are the maximal planar graphs formed by repeatedly splitting triangular faces into triples of smaller triangles.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Equivalently, they are the planar 3-trees.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Strangulated graphs are the graphs in which every peripheral cycle is a triangle.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In a maximal planar graph (or more generally a polyhedral graph) the peripheral cycles are the faces, so maximal planar graphs are strangulated.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The strangulated graphs include also the chordal graphs, and are exactly the graphs that can be formed by clique-sums (without deleting edges) of complete graphs and maximal planar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Outerplanar graphs are graphs with an embedding in the plane such that all vertices belong to the unbounded face of the embedding.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Every outerplanar graph is planar, but the converse is not true: *K*4 is planar but not outerplanar.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A theorem similar to Kuratowski's states that a finite graph is outerplanar if and only if it does not contain a subdivision of *K*4 or of *K*2,3.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The above is a direct corollary of the fact that a graph G is outerplanar if the graph formed from G by adding a new vertex, with edges connecting it to all the other vertices, is a planar graph.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A 1-outerplanar embedding of a graph is the same as an outerplanar embedding.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] For *k* > 1 a planar embedding is k-outerplanar if removing the vertices on the outer face results in a (*k* − 1)-outerplanar embedding.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A graph is k-outerplanar if it has a k-outerplanar embedding.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A Halin graph is a graph formed from an undirected plane tree (with no degree-two nodes) by connecting its leaves into a cycle, in the order given by the plane embedding of the tree.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Equivalently, it is a polyhedral graph in which one face is adjacent to all the others.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Like outerplanar graphs, Halin graphs have low treewidth, making many algorithmic problems on them more easily solved than in unrestricted planar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] An upward planar graph is a directed acyclic graph that can be drawn in the plane with its edges as non-crossing curves that are consistently oriented in an upward direction.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Not every planar directed acyclic graph is upward planar, and it is NP-complete to test whether a given graph is upward planar.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A planar graph is said to be **convex** if all of its faces (including the outer face) are convex polygons.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Not all planar graphs have a convex embedding (e.g. the complete bipartite graph K2,4).
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A sufficient condition that a graph can be drawn convexly is that it is a subdivision of a 3-vertex-connected planar graph.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Tutte's spring theorem even states that for simple 3-vertex-connected planar graphs the position of the inner vertices can be chosen to be the average of its neighbors.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Word-representable planar graphs include triangle-free planar graphs and, more generally, 3-colourable planar graphs, as well as certain face subdivisions of triangular grid graphs, and certain triangulations of grid-covered cylinder graphs.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The asymptotic for the number of (labeled) planar graphs on n vertices is $g\cdot n^{-7/2}\cdot \gamma ^{n}\cdot n!$ , where $\gamma \approx 27.22687$ and $g\approx 0.43\times 10^{-5}$ .
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Almost all planar graphs have an exponential number of automorphisms.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The number of unlabeled (non-isomorphic) planar graphs on n vertices is between $27.2^{n}$ and $30.06^{n}$ .
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The four color theorem states that every planar graph is 4-colorable (i.e., 4-partite).
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Fáry's theorem states that every simple planar graph admits a representation as a planar straight-line graph.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A universal point set is a set of points such that every planar graph with *n* vertices has such an embedding with all vertices in the point set; there exist universal point sets of quadratic size, formed by taking a rectangular subset of the integer lattice.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Every simple outerplanar graph admits an embedding in the plane such that all vertices lie on a fixed circle and all edges are straight line segments that lie inside the disk and don't intersect, so *n*-vertex regular polygons are universal for outerplanar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Scheinerman's conjecture (now a theorem) states that every planar graph can be represented as an intersection graph of line segments in the plane.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The planar separator theorem states that every *n*-vertex planar graph can be partitioned into two subgraphs of size at most 2*n*/3 by the removal of $O({\sqrt {n}})$ vertices.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] As a consequence, planar graphs also have treewidth and branch-width O(√*n*).
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] The planar product structure theorem states that every planar graph is a subgraph of the strong graph product of a graph of treewidth at most 8 and a path.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] This result has been used to show that planar graphs have bounded queue number, bounded non-repetitive chromatic number, and universal graphs of near-linear size.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] It also has applications to vertex ranking and *p*-centered colouring of planar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] For two planar graphs with *v* vertices, it is possible to determine in time O(*v*) whether they are isomorphic or not (see also graph isomorphism problem).
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Any planar graph on n nodes has at most 8(n-2) maximal cliques, which implies that the class of planar graphs is a class with few cliques.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] According to Tutte's theorem on Hamiltonian cycles, every 4-vertex-connected planar graph has a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] An apex graph is a graph that may be made planar by the removal of one vertex, and a *k*-apex graph is a graph that may be made planar by the removal of at most *k* vertices.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A 1-planar graph is a graph that may be drawn in the plane with at most one simple crossing per edge, and a *k*-planar graph is a graph that may be drawn with at most *k* simple crossings per edge.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A map graph is a graph formed from a set of finitely many simply-connected interior-disjoint regions in the plane by connecting two regions when they share at least one boundary point.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] A toroidal graph is a graph that can be embedded without crossings on the torus.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] More generally, the genus of a graph is the minimum genus of a two-dimensional surface into which the graph may be embedded; planar graphs have genus zero and nonplanar toroidal graphs have genus one.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Every graph can be embedded without crossings into some (orientable, connected) closed two-dimensional surface (sphere with handles) and thus the genus of a graph is well defined.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Obviously, if the graph can be embedded without crossings into a (orientable, connected, closed) surface with genus g, it can be embedded without crossings into all (orientable, connected, closed) surfaces with greater or equal genus.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] There are also other concepts in graph theory that are called "X genus" with "X" some qualifier; in general these differ from the above defined concept of "genus" without any qualifier.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Especially the non-orientable genus of a graph (using non-orientable surfaces in its definition) is different for a general graph from the genus of that graph (using orientable surfaces in its definition).
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Any graph may be embedded into three-dimensional space without crossings.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] Also, in three dimensions the question about drawing the graph without crossings is trivial.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] However, a three-dimensional analogue of the planar graphs is provided by the linklessly embeddable graphs, graphs that can be embedded into three-dimensional space in such a way that no two cycles are topologically linked with each other.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In analogy to Kuratowski's and Wagner's characterizations of the planar graphs as being the graphs that do not contain *K*5 or *K*3,3 as a minor, the linklessly embeddable graphs may be characterized as the graphs that do not contain as a minor any of the seven graphs in the Petersen family.
[src:graph-minors/planar-graph] In analogy to the characterizations of the outerplanar and planar graphs as being the graphs with Colin de Verdière graph invariant at most two or three, the linklessly embeddable graphs are the graphs that have Colin de Verdière invariant at most four.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] In graph theory, the **Robertson–Seymour theorem** (also called the **graph minors theorem**) states that the undirected graphs, partially ordered by the graph minor relationship, form a well-quasi-ordering.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The Robertson–Seymour theorem is named after mathematicians Neil Robertson and Paul D.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Seymour, who proved it in a series of twenty papers spanning over 500 pages from 1983 to 2004.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Before its proof, the statement of the theorem was known as **Wagner's conjecture** after the German mathematician Klaus Wagner, although Wagner said he never conjectured it.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] A weaker result for trees is implied by Kruskal's tree theorem, which was conjectured in 1937 by Andrew Vázsonyi and proved in 1960 independently by Joseph Kruskal and S.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] A minor of an undirected graph G is any graph that may be obtained from G by a sequence of zero or more contractions of edges of G and deletions of edges and vertices of G .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] However, if graphs that are isomorphic may nonetheless be considered as distinct objects, then the minor ordering on graphs forms a preorder, a relation that is reflexive and transitive but not necessarily antisymmetric.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] A preorder is said to form a well-quasi-ordering if it contains neither an infinite descending chain nor an infinite antichain.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] For instance, the usual ordering on the non-negative integers is a well-quasi-ordering, but the same ordering on the set of all integers is not, because it contains the infinite descending chain 0, −1, −2, −3...
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Another example is the set of positive integers ordered by divisibility, which has no infinite descending chains, but where the prime numbers constitute an infinite antichain.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The Robertson–Seymour theorem states that finite undirected graphs and graph minors form a well-quasi-ordering.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The graph minor relationship does not contain any infinite descending chain, because each contraction or deletion reduces the number of edges and vertices of the graph (a non-negative integer).
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The nontrivial part of the theorem is that there are no infinite antichains, infinite sets of graphs that are all unrelated to each other by the minor ordering.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Another equivalent form of the theorem is that, in any infinite set ${\mathcal {S}}$ of graphs, there must be a pair of graphs one of which is a minor of the other.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The statement that every infinite set has finitely many minimal elements implies this form of the theorem, for if there are only finitely many minimal elements, then each of the remaining graphs must belong to a pair of this type with one of the minimal elements.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] And in the other direction, this form of the theorem implies the statement that there can be no infinite antichains, because an infinite antichain is a set that does not contain any pair related by the minor relation.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] A family ${\mathcal {F}}$ of graphs is said to be closed under the operation of taking minors if every minor of a graph in ${\mathcal {F}}$ also belongs to ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] If ${\mathcal {F}}$ is a minor-closed family, then let ${\mathcal {S}}$ be the class of graphs that are not in ${\mathcal {F}}$ (the complement of ${\mathcal {F}}$ ).
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] According to the Robertson–Seymour theorem, there exists a finite set ${\mathcal {H}}$ of minimal elements in ${\mathcal {S}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] These minimal elements form a forbidden graph characterization of ${\mathcal {F}}$ : the graphs in ${\mathcal {F}}$ are exactly the graphs that do not have any graph in ${\mathcal {H}}$ as a minor.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The members of ${\mathcal {H}}$ are called the **excluded minors** (or **forbidden minors**, or **minor-minimal obstructions**) for the family ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] For example, the planar graphs are closed under taking minors: contracting an edge in a planar graph, or removing edges or vertices from the graph, cannot destroy its planarity.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The existence of forbidden minor characterizations for all minor-closed graph families is an equivalent way of stating the Robertson–Seymour theorem.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] For, suppose that every minor-closed family ${\mathcal {F}}$ has a finite set ${\mathcal {H}}$ of minimal forbidden minors, and let ${\mathcal {S}}$ be any infinite set of graphs.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Determine ${\mathcal {F}}$ from ${\mathcal {S}}$ as the family of graphs that do not have a minor in ${\mathcal {S}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Then ${\mathcal {F}}$ is minor-closed and has a finite set ${\mathcal {H}}$ of minimal forbidden minors.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Let ${\mathcal {C}}$ be the complement of ${\mathcal {F}}$ . ${\mathcal {S}}$ is a subset of ${\mathcal {C}}$ since ${\mathcal {S}}$ and ${\mathcal {F}}$ are disjoint, and ${\mathcal {H}}$ are the minimal graphs in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Consider a graph G in ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] G cannot have a proper minor in ${\mathcal {S}}$ since G is minimal in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] At the same time, G must have a minor in S , since otherwise G would be an element in ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Therefore, G is an element in ${\mathcal {S}}$ , i.e., ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a subset of ${\mathcal {S}}$ , and all other graphs in ${\mathcal {S}}$ have a minor among the graphs in ${\mathcal {H}}$ , so ${\mathcal {H}}$ is the finite set of minimal elements of ${\mathcal {S}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] To demonstrate the other direction of the equivalence, assume that every set of graphs has a finite subset of minimal graphs and let a minor-closed set ${\mathcal {F}}$ be given.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] We want to find a set ${\mathcal {H}}$ of graphs such that a graph is in ${\mathcal {F}}$ if and only if it does not have a minor in ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Let ${\mathcal {E}}$ be the graphs which are not minors of any graph in ${\mathcal {F}}$ , and let ${\mathcal {H}}$ be the finite set of minimal graphs in ${\mathcal {E}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Assume first that G is in ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] G cannot have a minor in ${\mathcal {H}}$ since G is in ${\mathcal {F}}$ and ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a subset of ${\mathcal {E}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Now assume that G is not in ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Then G is not a minor of any graph in ${\mathcal {F}}$ , since ${\mathcal {F}}$ is minor-closed.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Therefore, G is in ${\mathcal {E}}$ , so G has a minor in ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Some examples of finite obstruction sets were already known for specific classes of graphs before the Robertson–Seymour theorem was proved.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] For example, the obstruction for the set of all forests is the loop graph (or, if one restricts to simple graphs, the cycle with three vertices).
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] This means that a graph is a forest if and only if none of its minors is the loop (or, the cycle with three vertices, respectively).
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The sole obstruction for the set of paths is the tree with four vertices, one of which has degree 3.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] In these cases, the obstruction set contains a single element, but in general this is not the case.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Wagner's theorem states that a graph is planar if and only if it has neither $K_{5}$ nor $K_{3,3}$ as a minor.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] In other words, the set $\{K_{5},K_{3,3}\}$ is an obstruction set for the set of all planar graphs, and in fact the unique minimal obstruction set.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] A similar theorem states that $K_{4}$ and $K_{2,3}$ are the forbidden minors for the set of outerplanar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Although the Robertson–Seymour theorem extends these results to arbitrary minor-closed graph families, it is not a complete substitute for these results, because it does not provide an explicit description of the obstruction set for any family.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] For example, it tells us that the set of toroidal graphs has a finite obstruction set, but it does not provide any such set.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The complete set of forbidden minors for toroidal graphs remains unknown, but it contains at least 17,535 graphs.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The Robertson–Seymour theorem has an important consequence in computational complexity, due to the proof by Robertson and Seymour that, for each fixed graph H , there is a polynomial time algorithm for testing whether a graph has H as a minor.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] This algorithm's running time is cubic (in the size of the graph to check), though with a constant factor that depends superpolynomially on the size of the minor H .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The running time has been improved to quadratic by Kawarabayashi, Kobayashi, and Reed.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] As a result, for every minor-closed family ${\mathcal {F}}$ , there is polynomial time algorithm for testing whether a graph belongs to ${\mathcal {F}}$ : check whether the given graph contains H for each forbidden minor H in the obstruction set of ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] However, this method requires a specific finite obstruction set to work, and the theorem does not provide one.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] The theorem proves that such a finite obstruction set exists, and therefore the problem is polynomial because of the above algorithm.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] However, the algorithm can be used in practice only if such a finite obstruction set is provided.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] As a result, the theorem proves that the problem can be solved in polynomial time, but does not provide a concrete polynomial-time algorithm for solving it.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Such proofs of polynomiality are non-constructive: they prove polynomiality of problems without providing an explicit polynomial-time algorithm.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] In many specific cases, checking whether a graph is in a given minor-closed family can be done more efficiently: for example, checking whether a graph is planar can be done in linear time.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] For graph invariants with the property that, for each k , the graphs with invariant at most k are minor-closed, the same method applies.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] A problem with this property, that it can be solved in polynomial time for any fixed k with an exponent that does not depend on k , is known as fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] However, this method does not directly provide a single fixed-parameter-tractable algorithm for computing the parameter value for a given graph with unknown k , because of the difficulty of determining the set of forbidden minors.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Additionally, the large constant factors involved in these results make them highly impractical.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Therefore, the development of explicit fixed-parameter algorithms for these problems, with improved dependence on k , has continued to be an important line of research.
[src:graph-minors/robertson-seymour-theorem] Friedman uses this result on simple subcubic graphs to construct the fast-growing function, SSCG.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] In graph theory, a **tree decomposition** is a mapping of a graph into a tree that can be used to define the treewidth of the graph and speed up solving certain computational problems on the graph.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Tree decompositions are also called **junction trees**, **clique trees**, or **join trees**.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] They play an important role in problems like probabilistic inference, constraint satisfaction, query optimization, and matrix decomposition.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] The concept of tree decomposition was originally introduced by Rudolf Halin (1976).
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Later it was rediscovered by Neil Robertson and Paul Seymour (1984) and has since been studied by many other authors.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Intuitively, a tree decomposition represents the vertices of a given graph G as subtrees of a tree, in such a way that vertices in G are adjacent only when the corresponding subtrees intersect.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Thus, G forms a subgraph of the intersection graph of the subtrees.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] The full intersection graph is a chordal graph.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Each subtree associates a graph vertex with a set of tree nodes.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] To define this formally, we represent each tree node as the set of vertices associated with it.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] For every edge (*v*, *w*) in the graph, there is a subset Xi that contains both v and w.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] That is, vertices are adjacent in the graph only when the corresponding subtrees have a node in common.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] If Xi and Xj both contain a vertex v, then all nodes Xk of the tree in the (unique) path between Xi and Xj contain v as well.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] That is, the nodes associated with vertex v form a connected subset of T.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] This is also known as coherence, or the *running intersection property*.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] It can be stated equivalently that if Xi, Xj and Xk are nodes, and Xk is on the path from Xi to Xj, then $X_{i}\cap X_{j}\subseteq X_{k}$ .
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] The tree decomposition of a graph is far from unique; for example, a trivial tree decomposition contains all vertices of the graph in its single root node.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] A tree decomposition in which the underlying tree is a path graph is called a path decomposition, and the width parameter derived from these special types of tree decompositions is known as pathwidth.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] The *width* of a tree decomposition is the size of its largest set Xi minus one.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] The treewidth tw(*G*) of a graph G is the minimum width among all possible tree decompositions of G.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] In this definition, the size of the largest set is diminished by one in order to make the treewidth of a tree equal to one.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Treewidth may also be defined from other structures than tree decompositions, including chordal graphs, brambles, and havens.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] It is NP-complete to determine whether a given graph G has treewidth at most a given variable k.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] However, when k is any fixed constant, the graphs with treewidth k can be recognized, and a width k tree decomposition constructed for them, in linear time.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] The time dependence of this algorithm on k is an exponential function of *k*3.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] At the beginning of the 1970s, it was observed that a large class of combinatorial optimization problems defined on graphs could be efficiently solved by non-serial dynamic programming as long as the graph had a bounded *dimension*, a parameter related to treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Later, several authors independently observed, at the end of the 1980s, that many algorithmic problems that are NP-complete for arbitrary graphs may be solved efficiently by dynamic programming for graphs of bounded treewidth, using the tree-decompositions of these graphs.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] As an example, consider the problem of finding the maximum independent set in a graph of treewidth k.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] To solve this problem, first choose one of the nodes of the tree decomposition to be the root, arbitrarily.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] For a node Xi of the tree decomposition, let Di be the union of the sets Xj descending from Xi.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] where the sum in the calculation of $A(S,i)$ is over the children of node Xi.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] At each node or edge, there are at most 2*k* sets S for which we need to calculate these values, so if k is a constant then the whole calculation takes constant time per edge or node.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] The size of the maximum independent set is the largest value stored at the root node, and the maximum independent set itself can be found (as is standard in dynamic programming algorithms) by backtracking through these stored values starting from this largest value.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Thus, in graphs of bounded treewidth, the maximum independent set problem may be solved in linear time.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] Similar algorithms apply to many other graph problems.
[src:graph-minors/tree-decomposition] This dynamic programming approach is used in machine learning via the junction tree algorithm for belief propagation in graphs of bounded treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] In graph theory, the **treewidth** of an undirected graph is an integer number which specifies, informally, how far the graph is from being a tree.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The smallest treewidth is 1; the graphs with treewidth 1 are exactly the trees and the forests.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] An example of graphs with treewidth at most 2 are the series–parallel graphs.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The maximal graphs with treewidth exactly k are called *k-trees*, and the graphs with treewidth at most k are called *partial k-trees*.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Many other well-studied graph families also have bounded treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Treewidth is commonly used as a parameter in the parameterized complexity analysis of graph algorithms.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Many algorithms that are NP-hard for general graphs, become easier when the treewidth is bounded by a constant.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The concept of treewidth was originally introduced by Umberto Bertelè and Francesco Brioschi (1972) under the name of *dimension*.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] It was later rediscovered by Rudolf Halin (1976), based on properties that it shares with a different graph parameter, the Hadwiger number.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Later it was again rediscovered by Neil Robertson and Paul Seymour (1984) and has since been studied by many other authors.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] A tree decomposition of a graph $G=(V,E)$ is a tree T in which each node is associated with a subset of vertices called a "bag".
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] (The term *node* is used to refer to a vertex of T to avoid confusion with vertices of G ).
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] If bags $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ both contain a vertex v , then all bags $X_{k}$ associated with nodes in the (unique) path of T between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ also contain v as well.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Equivalently, the bags containing vertex v are associated with a connected subtree of T .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] For every edge $(v,w)$ in the graph, there is at least one bag $X_{i}$ that contains both v and w .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] That is, vertices are adjacent in the graph only when their corresponding subtrees have a node in common.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The *width* of a tree decomposition is the size of its largest bag $X_{i}$ minus one.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The **treewidth** $\operatorname {tw} (G)$ of a graph G is the minimum width among all possible tree decompositions of G .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Equivalently, the treewidth of G is one less than the size of the largest clique in the chordal graph containing G with the smallest clique number.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] A chordal graph with this clique size may be obtained by adding to G an edge between every two vertices for which at least one bag contains both vertices.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Treewidth may also be characterized in terms of havens, functions describing an evasion strategy for a certain pursuit–evasion game defined on a graph.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] A similar characterization can also be made using brambles, families of connected subgraphs that all touch each other (meaning either that they share a vertex or are connected by an edge).
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The order of a bramble is the smallest hitting set for the family of subgraphs, and the treewidth of a graph is one less than the maximum order of a bramble.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Every complete graph $K_{n}$ has treewidth $n-1$ .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] This is most easily seen using the definition of treewidth in terms of chordal graphs: the complete graph is already chordal, and adding more edges cannot reduce the size of its largest clique.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] A connected graph with at least two vertices has treewidth 1 if and only if it is a tree.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] A tree has treewidth one by the same reasoning as for complete graphs (namely, it is chordal, and has maximum clique size two).
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Conversely, if a graph has a cycle, then every chordal completion of the graph includes at least one triangle consisting of three consecutive vertices of the cycle, from which it follows that its treewidth is at least two.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] For any fixed constant k , the graphs of treewidth at most k are called the partial k -trees.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Other families of graphs with bounded treewidth include the cactus graphs, pseudoforests, series–parallel graphs, outerplanar graphs, Halin graphs, and Apollonian networks.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The control-flow graphs arising in the compilation of structured programs also have bounded treewidth, which allows certain tasks such as register allocation to be performed efficiently on them.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The planar graphs do not have bounded treewidth, because the $n\times n$ grid graph is a planar graph with treewidth exactly n .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Therefore, if F is a minor-closed graph family with bounded treewidth, it cannot include all planar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Conversely, if some planar graph cannot occur as a minor for graphs in family F , then there is a constant k such that all graphs in F have treewidth at most k .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] F is a minor-closed graph family that does not include all planar graphs.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] For every finite value of k , the graphs of treewidth at most k may be characterized by a finite set of forbidden minors.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] (That is, any graph of treewidth greater than k includes one of the graphs in the set as a minor.) Each of these sets of forbidden minors includes at least one planar graph.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] For larger values of k , the number of forbidden minors grows at least as quickly as an exponential function of ${\sqrt {k}}$ .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] However, known upper bounds on the size and number of forbidden minors are much higher than this lower bound.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] It is ${\mathsf {NP}}$ -complete to determine whether a given graph G has treewidth at most a given variable k .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The time dependence of this algorithm on k is exponential.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Due to the roles the treewidth plays in an enormous number of fields, different practical and theoretical algorithms computing the treewidth of a graph were developed.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Depending on the application on hand, one can prefer better approximation ratio, or better dependence in the running time from the size of the input or the treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The table below provides an overview of some of the treewidth algorithms.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Here k is the treewidth and n is the number of vertices of an input graph G .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Each of the algorithms outputs in time $f(k)\cdot g(n)$ a decomposition of width given in the Approximation column.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] For example, the algorithm of Bodlaender (1996) in time $2^{O(k^{3})}\cdot n$ either constructs a tree decomposition of the input graph G of width at most k or reports that the treewidth of G is more than k .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Similarly, the algorithm of Bodlaender et al.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] (2016) in time $2^{O(k)}\cdot n$ either constructs a tree decomposition of the input graph G of width at most $5k+4$ or reports that the treewidth of G is more than k .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Korhonen (2021) improved the width of the decomposition to $2k+1$ in the same running time.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] It is not known whether determining the treewidth of planar graphs is NP-complete, or whether their treewidth can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] In practice, an algorithm of Shoikhet & Geiger (1997) can determine the treewidth of graphs with up to 100 vertices and treewidth up to 11, finding a chordal completion of these graphs with the optimal treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] For larger graphs, one can use search-based techniques such as branch and bound search to compute the treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] These algorithms are anytime in that when stopped early, they will output an upper bound on the treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] An algorithm of this type was proposed in 2004 by Vibhav Gogate and Rina Dechter.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] To provide a lower bound on treewidth for the branches of this search, they construct a graph minor by repeatedly contracting an edge between a minimum degree vertex and one of its neighbors, until just one vertex remains.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The maximum of the minimum degree over these constructed minors is guaranteed to be a lower bound on the treewidth of the graph.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Alex Dow and Rich Korf further improved this algorithm using best-first search.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Later, several authors independently observed at the end of the 1980s that many algorithmic problems that are NP-complete for arbitrary graphs may be solved efficiently by dynamic programming for graphs of bounded treewidth, using the tree-decompositions of these graphs.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] As an example, the problem of coloring a graph of treewidth k may be solved by using a dynamic programming algorithm on a tree decomposition of the graph.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The resulting algorithm finds an optimal coloring of an n -vertex graph in time $O(k^{k+O(1)}n)$ , a time bound that makes this problem fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] For a large class of problems, there is a linear time algorithm to solve a problem from the class if a tree-decomposition with constant bounded treewidth is provided.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Specifically, Courcelle's theorem states that if a graph problem can be expressed in the logic of graphs using monadic second order logic, then it can be solved in linear time on graphs with bounded treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Consider for example the 3-coloring problem for graphs.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] For a graph $G=(V,E)$ , this problem asks if it is possible to assign each vertex $v\in V$ one of three colors such that no two adjacent vertices are assigned the same color.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The pathwidth of a graph has a very similar definition to treewidth via tree decompositions, but is restricted to tree decompositions in which the underlying tree of the decomposition is a path graph.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Alternatively, the pathwidth may be defined from interval graphs analogously to the definition of treewidth from chordal graphs.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] As a consequence, the pathwidth of a graph is always at least as large as its treewidth, but it can only be larger by a logarithmic factor.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Another parameter, the graph bandwidth, has an analogous definition from proper interval graphs, and is at least as large as the pathwidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Other related parameters include the tree-depth, a number that is bounded for a minor-closed graph family if and only if the family excludes a path, and the degeneracy, a measure of the sparsity of a graph that is at most equal to its treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Because the treewidth of an $n\times n$ grid graph is n , the treewidth of a graph G is always greater than or equal to the size of the largest square grid minor of G .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] In the other direction, the *grid minor theorem* by Robertson and Seymour shows that there exists an unbounded function f such that the largest square grid minor of a graph of treewidth k has size at least $f(k)$ .
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] (For the $\Omega$ notation in the lower bound, see big O notation.) Tighter bounds are known for restricted graph families, leading to efficient algorithms for many graph optimization problems on those families through the theory of bidimensionality.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Halin's grid theorem provides an analogue of the relation between treewidth and grid minor size for infinite graphs.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] A family F of graphs closed under taking subgraphs is said to have **bounded local treewidth**, or the **diameter-treewidth property**, if the treewidth of the graphs in the family is upper bounded by a function of their diameter.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] If the class is also assumed to be closed under taking minors, then F has bounded local treewidth if and only if one of the forbidden minors for F is an apex graph.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The original proofs of this result showed that treewidth in an apex-minor-free graph family grows at most doubly exponentially as a function of diameter; later this was reduced to singly exponential and finally to a linear bound.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Bounded local treewidth is closely related to the algorithmic theory of bidimensionality, and every graph property definable in first order logic can be decided for an apex-minor-free graph family in an amount of time that is only slightly superlinear.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] It is also possible for a class of graphs that is not closed under minors to have bounded local treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] In particular this is trivially true for a class of bounded degree graphs, as bounded diameter subgraphs have bounded size.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Another example is given by 1-planar graphs, graphs that can be drawn in the plane with one crossing per edge, and more generally for the graphs that can be drawn on a surface of bounded genus with a bounded number of crossings per edge.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] As with minor-closed graph families of bounded local treewidth, this property has pointed the way to efficient approximation algorithms for these graphs.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] Halin (1976) defines a class of graph parameters that he calls S-functions, which include the treewidth.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The set of all such functions forms a complete lattice under the operations of elementwise minimization and maximization.
[src:graph-minors/treewidth] The top element in this lattice is the treewidth, and the bottom element is the Hadwiger number, the size of the largest complete minor in the given graph.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] This was one of the earliest results in the theory of graph minors and can be seen as a forerunner of the Robertson–Seymour theorem.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] A planar embedding of a given graph is a drawing of the graph in the Euclidean plane, with points for its vertices and curves for its edges, in such a way that the only intersections between pairs of edges are at a common endpoint of the two edges.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] A minor of a given graph is another graph formed by deleting vertices, deleting edges, and contracting edges.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] When an edge is contracted, its two endpoints are merged to form a single vertex.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] In some versions of graph minor theory the graph resulting from a contraction is simplified by removing self-loops and multiple adjacencies, while in other version multigraphs are allowed, but this variation makes no difference to Wagner's theorem.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] The theorem states that every graph has either a planar embedding, or a minor of one of two types, the complete graph *K*5 or the complete bipartite graph *K*3,3.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] A *minor-minimal* non-planar graph is a graph that is not planar, but in which all proper minors (minors formed by at least one deletion or contraction) are planar.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] Another way of stating Wagner's theorem is that there are only two minor-minimal non-planar graphs, *K*5 and *K*3,3.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] Another result also sometimes known as Wagner's theorem states that a four-connected graph is planar if and only if it has no *K*5 minor.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] That is, by assuming a higher level of connectivity, the graph *K*3,3 can be made unnecessary in the characterization, leaving only a single forbidden minor, *K*5.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] Correspondingly, the Kelmans–Seymour conjecture states that a 5-connected graph is planar if and only if it does not have *K*5 as a topological minor.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] Wagner published both theorems in 1937, subsequent to the 1930 publication of Kuratowski's theorem, according to which a graph is planar if and only if it does not contain as a subgraph a subdivision of one of the same two forbidden graphs *K*5 and *K*3,3.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] In a sense, Kuratowski's theorem is stronger than Wagner's theorem: a subdivision can be converted into a minor of the same type by contracting all but one edge in each path formed by the subdivision process, but converting a minor into a subdivision of the same type is not always possible.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] However, in the case of the two graphs *K*5 and *K*3,3, it is straightforward to prove that a graph that has at least one of these two graphs as a minor also has at least one of them as a subdivision, so the two theorems are equivalent.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] One consequence of the stronger version of Wagner's theorem for four-connected graphs is to characterize the graphs that do not have a *K*5 minor.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] The theorem can be rephrased as stating that every such graph is either planar or it can be decomposed into simpler pieces.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] Using this idea, the *K*5-minor-free graphs may be characterized as the graphs that can be formed as combinations of planar graphs and the eight-vertex Wagner graph, glued together by clique-sum operations.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] For instance, *K*3,3 can be formed in this way as a clique-sum of three planar graphs, each of which is a copy of the tetrahedral graph *K*4.
[src:graph-minors/wagner-s-theorem] Analogues of Wagner's theorem can also be extended to the theory of matroids: in particular, the same two graphs *K*5 and *K*3,3 (along with three other forbidden configurations) appear in a characterization of the graphic matroids by forbidden matroid minors.
